Files:
- platform/cli/src/commands/start.ts (two separate fixes)

Context:
This is the main server start command. It checks port availability before starting and compares CLI vs bundled server versions.

Fix 1 — Version warning (lines 416-422):
```typescript
const printVersionWarning = (): void => {
  if (cliVersion && serverVersion && cliVersion !== serverVersion) {
    console.log(pc.yellow(`  Warning: CLI version (v${cliVersion}) does not match MCP server (v${serverVersion}).`));
    console.log(pc.dim('  Run: npm install -g @opentabs-dev/cli@latest'));
    console.log('');
  }
};
```
Change to distinguish direction:
- When cliVersion > serverVersion (semver compare): 'Restart the server to update it to the latest version.'
- When cliVersion < serverVersion: keep the existing 'npm install -g @opentabs-dev/cli@latest' message
Use simple string semver comparison: compare numeric parts by splitting on '.' and comparing as integers.

Fix 2 — Port conflict (lines 373-381):
```typescript
if (portInUse) {
  console.error(pc.red(`Error: Port ${port} is already in use.`));
  console.error(
    port === 9515
      ? 'Another OpenTabs server may already be running. Use --port to specify a different port.'
      : `Use a different port with: opentabs start --port <number>`,
  );
  process.exit(1);
}
```
Before printing the error, do a fast health check: GET http://127.0.0.1:{port}/health with 1.5s timeout. If the response includes header 'x-opentabs-version', it's our server. In that case:
```
console.error(pc.red(`Error: OpenTabs is already running on port ${port}.`))
console.error(`Stop it with: opentabs stop${port !== 9515 ? ` --port ${port}` : ''}`)
```
If the health check fails or the port isn't OpenTabs, use existing messages.

Constraints:
- Do NOT change the port-is-OpenTabs detection logic in status.ts or elsewhere — only fix start.ts
- The health check must use AbortSignal.timeout() and catch all errors silently
- getCliVersion() and getMcpServerVersion() already exist and return string versions — use those
- import fetch is already available in Node.js 22+

Files:
- platform/cli/src/commands/tool.ts (fix the tool schema not-found output)
- platform/mcp-server/src/mcp-tool-dispatch.ts (fix the disabled browser tool message)

Fix 1 — tool schema not-found (tool.ts lines 208-219):
```typescript
const tool = tools.find(t => t.name === name);
if (!tool) {
  console.error(pc.red(`Tool "${name}" not found.`));
  console.error();
  const names = tools.map(t => t.name).sort();
  if (names.length > 0) {
    console.error(`Available tools:`);
    for (const n of names) {
      console.error(`  ${pc.cyan(n)}`);
    }
  }
  process.exit(1);
}
```
Change to:
```typescript
if (!tool) {
  console.error(pc.red(`Tool "${name}" not found.`));
  console.error(`Run ${pc.cyan('opentabs tool list')} to see all available tools.`);
  process.exit(1);
}
```
Do NOT remove the `tools.find` line or the surrounding fetch/error handling. Only replace the not-found block.

Fix 2 — disabled browser tool message (mcp-tool-dispatch.ts line 258):
Current:
```typescript
text: `Tool "${toolName}" is currently disabled. Ask the user to enable it in the OpenTabs side panel.`,
```
Change to:
```typescript
text: `Tool "${toolName}" is currently disabled.\n\nTo enable it:\n- In the OpenTabs side panel: toggle the tool on\n- Via CLI: opentabs config set plugin-permission.browser-tool auto (enables all browser tools)\n- Via CLI: opentabs config set tool-permission.browser-tool.${toolName} auto (enables this tool only)`,
```
This message serves both AI agents (who relay it to users) and humans running opentabs tool call directly.

Constraints:
- Do NOT change the plugin tool disabled message (lines 331-353) — that has different review flow logic
- Do NOT change tool list output or tool call success path
